There are Muslims all over India and the world. But Meitei Pangals are only in Manipur and that should not be forgotten.         I would like to make a point regarding the genesis of the word "Pangal". This is my opinion based on facts, common sense and logic. Bengalis (irrespective of religion) are basically divided into two "groups" ie: Bengalis from West Bengal and those from present day Bangladesh. The WB Bengalis are called "ghotis" while that from Bangladesh are called "bongals". This grouping is purely based on their geographical location. When the Bongal Muslims (mostly from Sylhet) came to Manipur in the 1500s and 1600s, they were called as Pangals as the Meiteis could not pronounce the word "bongals" properly. And this became the byword as the word "pangal"/strength is in the Meitei lexicon. By this reasoning, Shanti Das Gosain (who was from Sylhet and a Hindu) is also a Pangal/Bongal who came in 1700s.

This is how history is manipulated and used by your masters when you don't guard your own.   History has always been monopolised by those agencies in power. It has been dictated and made to be accepted. When knowledge is subjected to such monopoly, it doesnt stay away from the power politics of distorting history for their own benefits and convenience. When your time dimension is let to be manipulated,distorted and misinterpreted, the space you exist will be distorted. And the space doesn't necessarily mean your geographical space, but also your economic, social and political space. This beautifully serves the master to swing the politics towards his gain.   In Manipur, we see distortions every where. And the recent being the one where attempts were made to distort the history of Pangals by some agents who have established their positions accepted in the society championing the cause for "Undivided Manipur" \- a cause that surely attracts hearts of many but hollow to its bone.   When you talk about undivided Manipur, what sort of undivided Manipur you are visioning. Is it the same unequal, highly skewed space to serve the status quo? Or is it otherwise?   ~ Himat Tampakmayum
